name: FontAwesome

aliases.name: Icon
aliases.comment:
Information on how an icon should be rendered. In general, you shouldn't need to interact directly with this type -
it should generally only exist in a chain of operations to display an icon.

Adding titles or using masking require that the icon has a unique id. This is because references are made in the HTML
via the HTML `id` attribute, which must be unique on the page. Views with an id will have the `WithId`
type and will therefore work with those options, while ones that have the `WithoutId` type won't.

aliases.name: IconDef
aliases.comment:
The definition of an icon.

You will find these in the modules for the different IconDef packs (e.g: `FontAwesome.Solid.Definition`).
You should never need to define these or change them yourself (but you can to create custom icons).

Generally you want to work with `Icon` instead, which can be found in the parent packs.
aliases.type: { prefix : String.String, name : String.String, size : ( Basics.Int, Basics.Int ), paths : ( String.String, Maybe.Maybe String.String ) }

aliases.name: WithId
aliases.comment:
Indicates that the presentation has an id, which lets you use `titled` and `masked`. For more on why those features
are "locked" like this, see the documentation for the `View` type above.

aliases.name: WithoutId
aliases.comment:
Indicates that the presentation does not have an id, which means you can't use `titled` and `masked`. For more on
why those features are "locked" like this, see the documentation for the `View` type above.

values.name: masked
values.comment:
Sets an outer icon that the main icon is masking (i.e.: the initial icon will become a "cut out" of this outer
icon). This creates true transparency.

Note that this can only be applied where the icon to be masked has an id unique on the page as it uses that id under the
hood in the HTML. Use `withId` to add one.
values.type: FontAwesome.Icon FontAwesome.WithId -> FontAwesome.Icon hasId -> FontAwesome.Icon hasId

values.name: present
values.comment:
Gets a basic presentation of an icon.

If you do nothing else an pass this to view, the icon will be presented as semantically meaningless (i.e: purely
decorative) and will be hidden from accessibility tools. If you need the icon to have semantic meaning then using
`titled` will change that.

values.name: styled
values.comment:
Add the given attributes to the icon's presentation. These will be applied to the icon when viewed.
Note the icon is an `svg` tag, and it appears that using `Html.Attribute.class` will remove any `Svg.Attribute.class`
values that are set, including FontAwesome ones that make the icon work, so make sure to use `Svg.Attribute.class` with
this.

Due to this taking `Svg.Attribute Never` you can't use attributes that can
produce messages. You can use `viewWithAttributes` to add such attributes if
required.
values.type: List.List (Svg.Attribute Basics.Never) -> FontAwesome.Icon hasId -> FontAwesome.Icon hasId

values.name: titled
values.comment:
Sets the title of the presented icon. This will make the icon semantically meaningful, and as such it won't be
hidden from accessibility tools.

Note that this can only be applied where the icon has an id unique on the page as it uses that id under the hood in the
HTML. Use `withId` to add one.

values.name: transform
values.comment: Add the given transforms to the icon's presentation. These will be applied to the icon when viewed.
values.type: List.List FontAwesome.Transforms.Transform -> FontAwesome.Icon hasId -> FontAwesome.Icon hasId

values.name: view
values.comment: Render the given icon to HTML.

values.name: withId
values.comment:
Set the HTML id for the icon presentation to the given value. This must be unique on the page.

The FontAwesome JavaScript library generates random ids for this. Doing this in elm is a little more cumbersome, but
is possible if you need to dynamically generate items and don't have existing ids to work from. Please see
[the `elm-fontawesome-example` repository](https://github.com/Lattyware/elm-fontawesome-example) for an example of this.

name: FontAwesome.Layering

values.name: counter
values.comment:
Adds a counter to the top right of your icons. Can be positioned with `layersBottomLeft`, `layersBottomRight`,
`layersTopLeft` and the default `layersTopRight`. Overflow text is truncated with an ellipsis.

values.name: layers
values.comment: Convenience function for producing layers of icons.
values.type: List.List (Html.Attribute msg) -> List.List (Html.Html msg) -> Html.Html msg

values.name: layersBottomLeft
values.comment: Apply the `fa-layers-bottom-left` class to the element.

values.name: layersBottomRight
values.comment: Apply the `fa-layers-bottom-right` class to the element.

values.name: layersTopLeft
values.comment: Apply the `fa-layers-top-left` class to the element.

values.name: layersTopRight
values.comment: Apply the `fa-layers-top-right` class to the element.

values.name: text
values.comment: Add inside your `layers` element to put text on top of an icon.

values.name: textTransformed
values.comment: Add inside your `layers` element to put text on top of an icon, applying the given transforms to it.
values.type: List.List (Html.Attribute msg) -> List.List FontAwesome.Transforms.Transform -> String.String -> Html.Html msg

name: FontAwesome.Styles
comment:
Helpers for adding the CSS required for FontAwesome to your page.

@docs css

values.name: css
values.comment: Generates the accompanying CSS that is necessary to correctly display icons.

name: FontAwesome.Svg
comment:
Rendering icons for use in SVG.

@docs view

values.name: view
values.comment:
View an icon as an SVG node.

Note this only supports some features, as some happen at the SVG level. For
example, set titles, attributes, and roles will be ignored.

name: FontAwesome.Transforms

values.name: down
values.comment: Transform the icon by repositioning it downwards by the given amount. Units are 1/16em.

values.name: flipH
values.comment: Transform the icon by flipping it on it's horizontal axis.

values.name: flipV
values.comment: Transform the icon by flipping it on it's vertical axis.

values.name: grow
values.comment: Transform the icon by growing it by the given amount. Units are 1/16em.

values.name: left
values.comment: Transform the icon by repositioning it leftwards by the given amount. Units are 1/16em.

values.name: right
values.comment: Transform the icon by repositioning it rightwards by the given amount. Units are 1/16em.

values.name: rotate
values.comment:
Transform the icon by rotating it by the given number of degrees clockwise (negateative numbers will produce an
anticlockwise rotation.

values.name: shrink
values.comment: Transform the icon by shrinking it by the given amount. Units are 1/16em.

values.name: up
values.comment: Transform the icon by repositioning it upwards by the given amount. Units are 1/16em.
